@NODE "Requirements" "What you need to run it!"
@NEXT "Installation"
@PREV "Disclaimer"

What you need to run this is:

An Amiga.
System2.x or higher installed on the above mentioned thing. 
Beeing a GM for a SW-RPG-campain, or beeing a player in such a campain
is not really nescessary, but it might help. 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation" "How to install it"
@NEXT "Usage"
@PREV "Requirements"

Well, you're reading this file, which implies you've succeeded to unpack the 
archive. And that, ladies and gentlemen (and everyone else), is all you have
to do. Go to the directory where you unpacked the archive, and type AmiRoller
to start, or, start it via WB. Anything goes. 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "How to use it"
@NEXT "FeedBugs"
@PREV "Installation"

When starting AmiRoller a window will appear with a few gadgets to play around
with. 

In the one labeled "Number of dices" you should fill in the number of 
skill/attribute dices the characther has. 

In the one labeled "Bonus" you should fill in the bonus (or pips) the character
has on this skill/attribute. 

Example: The Gamorrean Otto has 6D+2 in Melee Combat, thus "Number of dices"
should be 6, and "bonus" 2. 

In the one labeled "Number of rolls" you should fill in how many actions the
character does in the round.

Example: The same Gamorrean(Otto) wanna do 4 attacks in the same round, thus
"Number of rolls" should be 4. The program will subtract the penalty for 
multiple actions. 

The checkbox labeled "Use Wild die" is quite obvious. If the roll requires a
wilddie, leave the box checked, if not, unmark it. 

When everything is set to your satisfaction, click on the "Roll"-button
and another window will open, with the results in it. When you don't need
the result any longer, just click on the Close-gadget. 

@ENDNODE

@NODE "FeedBugs" "Buggy? Prolly. Want it to work properly? Read this."
@NEXT "Changes"
@PREV "Usage"

Even in such a small and inoffensive program like this, those darn bugs
